===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm|crien}}, from {{der|en|fro|crier||to announce publicly, proclaim, scream, shout}} (whence {{cog|ML.|crīdō||to cry out, shout, publish, proclaim}}), from {{der|en|frk|*kritan|*krītan|to cry, cry out, publish}}, from {{der|en|gem-pro|*krītaną||to cry out, shout}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*greyd-||to shout}}. Cognate with {{cog|stq|kriete||to cry}}, {{cog|nl|krijten||to cry}} and {{m|nl|krijsen||to shriek}}, {{cog|nds-de|krieten||to cry, call out, shriek}}, {{cog|de|kreißen||to cry loudly, wail, groan}}, {{cog|got|𐌺𐍂𐌴𐌹𐍄𐌰𐌽||to cry, scream, call out}}, Latin {{m|la|gingrītus||the cackling of geese}}, {{cog|mga|grith||a cry}}, {{cog|cy|gryd||a scream}}.

{{rel-top|etymology note}}
Alternate etymology connects the {{cog|ML.|-}} word to {{cog|la|queror||to complain}} through the form {{m|la|quiritō||to wail, shriek}}, though the phonetic and semantic developments are difficult to trace.

{{cog|enm|crien}} eventually displaced native {{cog|enm|galen||to cry out}} (from {{cog|ang|galan}}), {{cog|enm|greden||to cry out}} (from {{cog|ang|grǣdan}}), {{cog|enm|yermen||to bellow, mourn, lament}} (from {{cog|ang|ġierman}}), {{cog|enm|hoen|hooen, hoen|to cry out}} (from {{cog|non|hóa}}), {{cog|enm|remen||to cry, shout}} (from {{cog|ang|hrīeman}}, compare {{cog|ang|hrēam||noise, outcry, lamentation, alarm}}), {{cog|enm|gretan|greten, graten|to weep, cry, lament}} (from {{cog|ang|grǣtan}} and {{cog|non|gráta}}). More at {{m|en|greet}}, {{m|en|regret}}.
